<br>
By David Hsieh <br>
<br>
BEIJING - China's continued growth cannot be guaranteed unless urbanisation keeps pace with rapid industrialisation and economic expansion, according to a new report.<br>
<br>
It calls for the three emerging super-cities - along the Beijing-Tianjin corridor, the Changjiang River delta, and the Pearl River delta - to be better managed and speeded up to spur growth.<br>
<br>
Commissioned by the Association of Chinese Mayors, the first China Urban Development Report (2001-2002) brought together 100 Chinese and foreign experts to begin mapping out the nation's strategy for urbanisation over the next five decades.<br>
<br>
The massive report constructs an overarching framework that also envisages the creation of several key economic belts and the designation of key cities in China's central and western regions.<br>
<br>
The report foresees that these areas will eventually be inhabited by over half of the country's population and produce 80 per cent of the country's Gross Domestic Product.<br>
<br>
They are also expected to account for 90 per cent of industrial output and 95 per cent of total trade, the report added.<br>
<br>
But China needed a new strategy to guide and accelerate urbanisation to ensure continued rapid growth, said Professor Niu Wenyuan, the report's leading scientist.<br>
<br>
The head of the China-USA Joint Centre for the Environment and Development at the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) believes that the country's urbanisation lags far behind its rapid industrialisation and economic expansion.<br>
<br>
Analysing rates of urbanisation and wealth accumulation worldwide, Prof Niu argues that the higher the rate of urbanisation, the faster the creation and accumulation of wealth.<br>
<br>
China's urbanisation rate now is around 37 per cent, compared with 75 per cent or higher in the wealthiest countries. To join the club of advanced countries, China will need to transform 500 million to 600 million peasants into economically active city-dwellers.<br>
<br>
Yet, Chinese cities must not balloon out of control like Mexico City, metro Manila, Jakarta, and other Third World urban centres.<br>
<br>
Instead, the super-cities should be clusters of large, medium-sized and small cities forming 'a virtuous circle for the exchange of goods, information, capital, personnel, and technology', said the professor.<br>
<br>
Such metro areas are already shaping up on the Pearl River delta and on the Changjiang River delta connecting Shanghai to Nanjing and Ningbo. A third mega-city, encompassing Beijing-Tianjin-Tanggu and other cities near and along the Bohai Sea coast to Qinhuangdao, is now being discussed actively by scholars and legislators.<br>
<br>
Prof Niu and his team propose that populations in poor rural areas move out so that, eventually, only 20 per cent of the country's peasants are left to till the land.<br>
<br>
It will cost about 25,000 yuan (S$5,250) to relocate each peasant and provide for his living and training needs.<br>
<br>
To achieve 75 per cent urbanisation by 2050, China will need to relocate 10 million to 12 million peasants each year.<br>
<br>
The cost of this massive exercise is expected to reach 350 billion yuan a year, or 4 per cent of the GDP in 2000.<br>
<br>
This strategy must aim to avoid creating urban poverty, traffic congestion, environmental degradation and other problems afflicting the world's biggest cities.<br>
<br>
Renowned CAS academician He Zuoxiu, who has reviewed the report, agreed with its main thrust, but argued that much political will has to be exercised to fix the existing ills in Chinese cities.<br>
<br>
As an example, he cited Beijing's promotion of the car industry. 'This is diametrically opposed to new directions in urban development,' he noted.<br>
